        <Title>First Steps AndroidStudio</Title>
        <Content><![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM 'http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd'><en-note style=
"word-wrap: break-word; -webkit-nbsp-mode: space; -webkit-line-break: after-white-space;">

<ul>
<li>install Android Studio and create your first project<br /></li>
<li>AVD Manager</li>
<ul>
<li>used for creating and selecting a virtual device</li>
<li>select system image</li>
<ul>
<li>e.g. in the course it is Q (API level 29, since it is new and
stable version)</li>
</ul>
</ul>
<li>for simulation kvm might be required on Linux</li>
<ul>
<li>has to be enabled in BIOS</li>
<li>some packages are required on linux, qemu etc.</li>
<li>command to query kvm support</li>
<ul>
<li>dmesg | grep -i kvm</li>
</ul>
</ul>
<li>when there is issues running the emulator on Linux</li>
<ul>
<li>cd to&nbsp;/home/wolfi/Android/Sdk/tools/</li>
<li>set variable&nbsp;
<ul>
<li>export ANDROID_EMULATOR_DEBUG=1</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>run emulator</li>
<ul>
<li>/emulator -avd Pixel_3a_API_30_x86</li>
</ul>
<li><br /></li>
</ul>
<li>perhaps better success using flatpak "Android-studio" on MX
Linux?</li>
</ul>
<div><br /></div>
<div>
<ul>
<li>/usr/bin/flatpak run --branch=stable --arch=x86_64
--command=android-studio com.google.AndroidStudio<br /></li>
<li>better use snapd perhaps?</li>
<ul>
<li><a href="https://snapcraft.io/install/android-studio/debian"
title=
"https://snapcraft.io/install/android-studio/debian">https://snapcraft.io/install/android-studio/debian</a><br />
</li>
</ul>
<li><br /></li>
</ul>
<div><br /></div>
</div>
<div><br /></div>
<div>for KVM acceleration follow:</div>
<div>
<ul>
<li><a href=
"https://developer.android.com/studio/run/emulator-acceleration?utm_source=android-studio#vm-linux"
title=
"https://developer.android.com/studio/run/emulator-acceleration?utm_source=android-studio#vm-linux">
https://developer.android.com/studio/run/emulator-acceleration?utm_source=android-studio#vm-linux</a><br />
</li>
</ul>
<div><br /></div>
</div>
<div>Note: simulator needs a lot of free space 7+ GB</div>
<div>
<ul>
<li>tricky to turn on developer mode on real phone</li>
<ul>
<li>tap 7 times on build number in about phone ("Ãœber das
Telefon")</li>
</ul>
<li>System &amp; Aktualisierung should have now developer
options</li>
</ul>
<div>To make it possible under a linux environment follow:</div>
</div>
<div>
<ul>
<li><a href="https://developer.android.com/studio/run/device"
title="https://developer.android.com/studio/run/device">https://developer.android.com/studio/run/device</a><br />
</li>
<ul>
<li>add user to plug</li>
</ul>
</ul>
</div>
<div><br /></div>
<div><br /></div>
</en-note>]]></Content>
